            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "When Dan McSweeney grew up in Morningside Heights over four decades ago, mom-and-pop shops were on every block, catering to longtime residents and Columbia students alike. To McSweeney, the area—featuring everything from legendary Chinese eatery Moon Palace to the homey College Inn—possessed a lot of character and local charm, with some small businesses helping to pioneer major literary and social movements like the Beat Generation and the movement for LGBTQ rights."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Then came the first national chains. Soon after, these iconic small businesses began to shut down one after another. And over the course of a decade, the area has become a haven for trendy and chain restaurants along Broadway and Amsterdam Avenue, with many locally owned restaurants struggling to hang on."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“What we’re experiencing in Morningside Heights is essentially corporatization of retail commerce, so chain stores have been moving in, and mom-and-pop shops unfortunately are dwindling,” McSweeney, who works at the Morningside Heights Historic District Committee, said. “I think many advocates in the community feel that this diminishes the local character and quality of life because locally owned businesses are a mainstay of local culture and … support networks or social networks.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Morningside Heights restaurant scene has changed drastically over the last few decades. More people started viewing dining as a social experience, and the culture surrounding dining changed with it. The sheer number of restaurants in the area has also grown, featuring an increasingly diverse selection of eateries that serve cuisines from across the globe."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yet as rents continue to rise due to factors like gentrification and food becomes even less affordable for people with lower incomes, this diversity is at risk. The relationship between the University and smaller non-Columbia tenant restaurants has also become increasingly fraught as more chain restaurants move into Columbia-owned properties."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Historically, [Columbia] always said that they would like to keep the neighborhood mom-and-pop type stores,” Alex Turboff, vice president of real estate at BCD, a real estate brokerage firm for restaurants and retail, said. “But what we’ve seen, especially on Broadway, is that the mom and pops are not able to pay the rent that the national and regional brands are able to support just because of throughput—the amount of bodies and people that come through the business—when the local operator may not achieve the same kind of levels as a national brand.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "<b>The growth of the chains and trendy restaurants</b>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "McSweeney, who has been working on an oral history project documenting the restaurant scene in Morningside Heights, recalled that only in the past decade has the growth of chain restaurants near campus skyrocketed. The sense of community that developed at local eateries has dwindled for McSweeney, who noted that the social aspect of the restaurant scene has become more of a distant memory."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“As these businesses get replaced, it seems mainly by chain stores or banks, people have a tendency to forget those shops,” McSweeney said. “The new landscape is not as conducive to supporting the idea of local culture—local shared memory because they’re corporate. The people who work in them or manage them or own them don’t necessarily have links to this neighborhood, and it’s more difficult to establish an ongoing relationship with the chain stores because they seem so remote and institutional.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Spectator analyzed data from 2008-21 on the evolution of the restaurant offerings around campus. From 2009 to 2019, 67 chain locations opened, with 32 of those being national chains and 35 of those being chains specific to New York City or the Northeast. In the same time period, only 33 chain locations closed, with 13 of those being national chains. Chains that opened multiple locations during this timespan include Starbucks, Dunkin', Subway, and Serafina."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Many of the locals interviewed noted that Morningside Heights and West Harlem look nothing like they did a few decades ago. McSweeney recalled how even 20 years ago, most food options in the area were locally owned and only had one or two locations near campus. Since eating out regularly was not as common and the fast casual concept had not yet gained traction, restaurants in the area were often family-owned and catered to both students and longtime residents. However, as rents rose and the University expanded, McSweeney started to notice a major shift in the neighborhood’s restaurant scene."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[The prices] would have been unthinkable—I think even 20 years ago, let alone 50 years ago, the prices being for the rent but also for the goods that are offered at the shops, if they're locally owned and they’re boutique type stores,” McSweeney said. “In Morningside Heights especially, it's not completely a free market because the institutions own the majority of the land in Morningside Heights. So there are certain parameters that the institutions place on the businesses that can potentially either emerge here or continue to operate here.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Kaaryn Nailor Simmons, director of the Columbia-Harlem Small Business Development Center, attributes these changes to the growth of economic opportunities, changes in immigration patterns, and shifts in food culture throughout the city. She noted that Morningside Heights followed a similar trend to the country as a whole, becoming more developed and wealthier over the last few decades."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[New York] is an interesting place because historically, it’s kind of a starting point for immigrants, and they live here for a number of decades. And then families kind of do well, and they move out to the suburbs, or they move to the Midwest or wherever it is,” Nailor Simmons said. “At the same time, there’s also been a population shift. There are more people just living in New York City; there’s eight million people living in New York City. When I was a kid, there were maybe four or five million people, but it’s a very different place than it was 30 years ago.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "These demographic shifts are reflected in the changing restaurant scene around campus. When Nailor Simmons was a child, for instance, getting a slice of pizza once a month was a big event, whereas now, her children expect a restaurant meal two or three times a week. The number of chains and fast casual restaurants in the area has increased in part because people’s lifestyles have transformed significantly."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“If we’re talking about restaurants in general, people like to eat, and they like to feel special. They like to feel like after a hard day of work or a hard day of caring for their family that everyone deserves a treat, and often, that’s what a restaurant does,” Nailor Simmons said. “You want to be treated a certain way, and you want to be nourished a certain way, and I think that’s kind of why the proliferation of restaurants has really been very important not just in New York and Upper Manhattan, but around the country.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Andre Neyrey, the owner and president of Blackwood Hospitality, the restaurant scene in Morningside Heights has historically never been as lively or diverse as the Upper West Side, and he noted that the scene “kind of died” at 96th Street. Because rents increased rapidly in Morningside Heights and less people from outside the area traveled to dine at Morningside Heights restaurants in comparison to those on the Upper West Side, smaller eateries struggled to attract the client base necessary to stay open."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, because Morningside Heights and West Harlem rents were cheaper in comparison to the Upper West Side, Neyrey noted that younger people moved into the area at higher rates. While the student population in campus housing has remained relatively constant over the past few decades, the area became overall younger and therefore trendier. Restaurateurs were more willing to take a risk and open more experimental or trendy spots, which led the overall restaurant scene to become less affordable. When newer and more expensive restaurants opened near campus, local restaurants had to fight even harder to compete with already successful concepts, leading to the closing of many longtime favorites."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The real median gross rent in Morningside Heights increased from <a href=\"https://furmancenter.org/neighborhoods/view/morningside-heights-hamilton\">$1,020 in 2006 to $1,530 in 2019</a>, which amounts to $18,360 per year. The median household income of the Morningside Heights area in 2019 was $69,540, which is extremely close to the median citywide household income at $70,590. However, the area also has an above-average poverty rate, at 19.6 percent in 2019 compared to 16 percent across the city. Between 1990 to 2010-2014, rents increased by 36.7 percent in Morningside Heights and Hamilton Heights."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In 2019, 29.3 percent of renter households in the area were severely rent burdened, meaning that they spent more than half of household income on rent. Due to these individuals’ dire financial conditions, they have little money to spend on food options, thereby making them more reliant on chain eateries or, in some cases, forcing them out of the area."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In 2019, in Central Harlem—where many chains and trendy restaurants have opened up recently—the <a href=\"https://furmancenter.org/neighborhoods/view/central-harlem\">median household income </a>was $55,870, 21 percent less than the citywide rate. While real median gross rent was cheaper in Central Harlem at $1,260 in 2019, or $15,120 per year, only 23.7 percent of renter households were severely rent burdened."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Yong Zhao, the CEO of Chinese fast casual eatery Junzi with five locations across New York and Connecticut, Junzi’s executives wanted to open the eatery’s second location by Columbia to build up its brand in an area with high foot traffic and competition along Broadway. Because opening up a restaurant is “very risky” in New York, Junzi’s executives desired a location that already attracted a younger demographic and had a thriving restaurant scene."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s also that sentiment of how when you enter a new market, you want to make sure you’re tapping into the tastemakers … Columbia’s campus and the surrounding population is exactly that niche market,” Nicky Chang, vice president of brand & design at Junzi, said. “The student body and the staff members and their families, in our opinion, are really like pacemakers in the New York market. They are relatively well traveled, and they have been exposed to really good food in New York.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Chains can thrive around Columbia because they have the resources to pay for skyrocketing rents, according to Anthony Advincula, director of communications at Restaurant Opportunities Centers United. As a student at the Columbia School of Journalism, Advincula remembered only being able to afford chains in the area since chains could drive down prices and outcompete smaller restaurants, in part because of the support they receive from policymakers."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[Chains] had the lease for 10 years, a much longer period as compared to [other] restaurant business owners. If you increase the rent of that, they don’t have enough resources or enough [of a] cushion to really support that,” Advincula said. “Ultimately, the business doesn’t survive. That’s very apparent in New York City and that’s why it all boils down to the corporation. They have bigger resources and bigger support systems because they lobby.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "table.html",
                "steps": [
                  "Between 2017 and 2018, the address 2955 Broadway went from being occupied by Vine Sushi & Sake, a non-chain restaurant, to Pret a Manger, a national chain.",
                  "Of the 39 non-chain restaurants on Broadway in 2008, 10 left their Broadway address at some point in the last 13 years. Between 2008 and 2021, the percentage of restaurants on Broadway that were national chains or New York City chains increased from 32 percent to 47 percent.",
                  "Between 2008 and 2021, the percentage of national and New York City chain restaurants on Amsterdam Avenue increased from 9 percent to 22 percent. In contrast, the percentage of national and New York City chain restaurants on Columbus Avenue and other surrounding areas decreased from 15.5 percent to 12.5 percent between that same period, with the majority of new restaurants in the area being non-chain restaurants."
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While the Columbia area has attracted the big name chains such as McDonald’s and Chipotle, many more upscale chain eateries, including Dig and Sweetgreen, have opened locations along Broadway. According to Eric Sarmiento, assistant professor in the department of geography at Texas State University, college towns have experienced a major growth in these more pricey student-oriented chain restaurants, which sometimes charge twice the price of more widespread chains."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“They’re not like McDonald’s or Taco Bell, the kinds of chains that flourish in low-income areas,” Sarmiento said. “They’re still cheap-quality, poor-quality fast food, but they’re more expensive. … I’ve been thinking of them as sort of like the Target of fast food, whereas McDonald’s is kind of more like the Walmart of fast food.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "By opening up locations near universities, Sarmiento believes these types of chains can make some profit by benefiting from economies of scale, a proportionate saving in costs from increased production levels. Neyrey attributes the growth of chains to their proximity to colleges, since students often frequent chains out of convenience and spread the word about them."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[College towns] drove all of the chain growth. Domino’s got started [in that] they kept opening by colleges because they … could deliver 30 of them into a dorm room,” Neyrey said. “But New York is unique in that Columbia in a small town would <i>be</i> the town. There’s a lot of students. They’re going to demand better quality stuff or different types of restaurants and more variety.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Neyrey, chain restaurants “either set the mark or they follow the mark.” He suspects that once the first few chains opened on Broadway, many others jumped on the bandwagon and looked for more visible locations next to other chains."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sarmiento, who also used to work at Labyrinth Books—which is now Book Culture—questioned the claim that chain restaurants really opened around Columbia to maximize profits. Although some chains have raised their prices considerably around Columbia compared to other parts of the city, many have kept their prices consistent, which when combined with sky-high rents leaves little room for significant profit margins. Sarmiento believes the business model of many nationwide chains makes it so that standard prices and high rents would be rather unsustainable."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Just by being kind of in prestigious neighborhoods with Columbia and obviously attracting the students, the faculty, the visiting scholars that are coming there, there’s maybe just sort of a cultural cachet for being in that area that somehow benefits them, even if they’re not making money off those spaces,” Sarmiento said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sarmiento also hypothesized that even just by opening in affluent or bustling areas like Morningside Heights, chains may even experience rises in stock prices. He believes there might be an analogue in the fast-food industry for what is occurring in the housing market, in which people are building far in excess of demand."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yet according to Nailor Simmons, rising rent is just one component of the growing commercialization of Morningside Heights and West Harlem. Up until around five or six years ago, areas like West and Central Harlem did not have near the number of restaurants as what are currently open, but with more people moving into the area and taking advantage of all that restaurants have to offer, more have proliferated in the area than ever before."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although increased rents played a role in the closure of many mom-and-pop restaurants nearby, Nailor Simmons also attributes these recent closures to restaurants not adapting to industry trends or being methodical about appealing to the area’s diverse demographic. Because restaurants have such tight margins, places that do not constantly think about numbers or about getting new clients will not survive in a hypercompetitive market. Nailor Simmons found that for many of the restaurants that closed pre-COVID-19, “operations were not, quite frankly, up to date, or their product mix was not current or exactly what the community was looking for at that time.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The more competition a restaurant has, the more that they have to actually go out and market themselves, [and] the more that they have to stay current,” Nailor Simmons said. “The thing with restaurants that people don’t always realize, it’s not a food business. It’s a hospitality business. So you have to really think through how are you creating a hospitable experience or a certain experience for your patrons.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "One aspect of these shifts is the reliance on online ordering and delivery, which has both helped and hindered chain restaurants and retailers. According to Kate Ascher, the Milstein professor of Urban Development at Graduate School of Architecture, Planning and Preservation, the emergence of online buying has led many retailers to close since people now have the convenience of ordering from anywhere for cheaper. In these empty storefronts previously occupied by shoe stores or clothing boutiques—which Ascher considers a vacuum of space—come businesses that cannot be replaced so easily: restaurants."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, to some extent, online ordering has hindered smaller businesses that cannot necessarily afford to advertise online or partner with delivery apps. When apps like DoorDash and Seamless take upwards of 30 percent of the total cost for themselves, restaurants without the economic security of larger chains either have to risk making little profit on every order or hiring their own delivery people, which is not only costly but detrimental to marketing to the community. Additionally, now that people can order food from anywhere in the city, trendier restaurants that have more appeal or name recognition may do more orders around campus."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Why would you necessarily limit yourself to the restaurants in the neighborhood, especially if you feel like those restaurants don’t have exactly what you want?” Nailor Simmons asked."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although delivery apps have lessened the importance of a restaurant’s immediate proximity to students, Neyrey believes that some chains seek locations around college campuses in order to increase publicity and expand their markets to new areas, even though they will not be making enormous profits per order."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“On Broadway, it’s kind of like a flagship, they may be hoping that people that are meeting at this restaurant now may be a customer for life,” Neyrey said. “They will make it up in volume. They’re not charging any more, but they may do a heavier foot traffic because there’s potential customers there. From a corporate standpoint they might need to just spur growth, trying to grow, and you run out of areas as a chain.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sarmiento does believe that because so many chains are Columbia tenants, the University may give these chains added stability by acting as a fair and just landlord. In addition to keeping rent prices rather stable over the last decade, for example, Columbia gave two months of free rent to its restaurant tenants at the start of the pandemic. Plenty of tenants have taken advantage of Columbia as a landlord, with 13 of the 24 restaurants that rent from the University—and were open as of June 2020—having multiple locations. Columbia has also recently signed tenant contracts with two new restaurants that also operate other locations throughout the city: Roberta’s and SAPPS."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Ascher, Columbia used to have a policy in which it would not rent its property to chain restaurants. However, this policy has since been altered, especially when many Columbia tenants along Broadway are indeed chains. Additionally, some on-campus food businesses like Joe Coffee Company are chains with locations all throughout the city."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Analena Hassberg, an assistant professor of ethnic and women’s studies at California State Polytechnic University, has studied food gentrification and is well acquainted with the nationwide phenomenon of strong relationships existing between universities and restaurant chains. This phenomenon is part of a broader trend wherein corporations and wealthy institutions can “skirt and evade the tax brackets and the kind of financial penalties that the rest of us are beholden to.” If a small business does not pay rent, for instance, then the owners are out on the street. Large chains like Chipotle, meanwhile, can occupy properties near campus for little to no rent and easily afford it."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[Chains] are creating space for themselves ... in these institutions where they know that there will be a captive audience,” Hassberg said. “It’s like having a restaurant in the airport. People are hungry, they’re going to pay five bucks for that water bottle when it’s only worth 75 cents.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Turboff, universities generally rent out to chain tenants because they are more comfortable with a recognizable brand that has both private equity and a strong customer base. With significant financial backing from investors and greater economic resources, chain restaurants make ideal tenants because they have a lower chance of missing a rent payment."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Landlords want reliable returns when they rent. Thinking of the landlord, when choosing between a new experimental business with a potentially exciting business plan and an established chain for whom, even if the individual locations struggle, there would be funding to pay the rent, from other sources, corporate headquarters or whatever. You might very well make the sort of economically rational choice to go with a chain business, rather than something less likely to pay the rent on time,” Aaron Passell, associate director of urban studies at Barnard, said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While chains and more upscale restaurants have sprouted up all around campus in the last few years, Broadway has seen considerably more commercialization than Amsterdam or Columbus Avenues. According to Turboff, the larger storefronts of properties along Broadway better lend themselves to the prototypical layout that many chains have; chains with more individualized storefronts would not look toward Columbus Avenue, whose three or four-story buildings have smaller footprints. Thus, more local businesses like delis or pizzerias often buy properties along Columbus since they require less space and do not need to fit Broadway’s box models."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“A lot of times the property along Broadway are bigger buildings that have allowed for more of a box,” Turboff said. “The layout of the space is more functional, they’re the right size, they’re the right width, they have less columns, they have more infrastructure in place in the way of higher electricity or the size of the water line. So those things can also lend itself to [why] wide national [chains] choose to go on Broadway versus perhaps going into a smaller building on Columbus.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Broadway’s positioning by the subway also likely contributed to the rapid commercialization of the street to a much greater extent than Amsterdam or Columbus Avenues, according to Neyrey."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s graphic, it’s visual. People are drawn to Broadway because there’s more activity on Broadway, it’s always been that way. … So you have a lot of pull, so when you have a lot more pull, traffic, visibility, subway stops, all of that plays into it with the foot traffic,” Neyrey said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Sharon Zukin, professor emerita of sociology at Brooklyn College and the City University of New York Graduate Center, shopping streets like Amsterdam Avenue and Columbus Avenue are more quiet and tend to have more diverse and trendy restaurants as compared to busier streets like Broadway. One of her colleagues noted that trendier restaurants like to open on smaller streets for aesthetic reasons, although Zukin also attributes this to rent disparities."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Those kinds of restaurants are particularly in [areas] where the income level is not really high. Those kinds of restaurants can't pay high rents,” Zukin said. “They would have to look on the smaller streets, not on the main streets, and also maybe … those kinds of restaurants want the aesthetic of small blocks, small footprints, meaning small size of the restaurant storefront, and more quiet, less traffic.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "National chains have faced little turnover, but some like Subway have recently closed in the area. There has, however, been significant turnover and churn along Broadway south of campus, particularly among small businesses and retail chains. Due to the development of online shopping, many retail and clothing stores have shuttered their doors recently, leaving many empty storefronts along Broadway."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“So there’s just been so much of a decline in the need to go into a store that it has hit retail across the city and other cities, obviously, in a big way, … which is why so much of that vacuum has been filled by restaurants, bars, stuff like that, things you can’t replace by being at home,” Ascher said. “That’s just a trend everywhere. That's what the real estate world is looking into now is that they want to have experiences. They want to make eating and drinking an experience, [and] pull people out because it’s really hard to pull people out to buy stuff."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Though many rents have dropped for many Broadway properties due to the prevalence of empty storefronts, some retail outlets have not received this cushion. When Ascher lived on Broadway and 105th Street, she found that a longstanding restaurant had to close because the landlord wanted too much rent after its lease was up. This massive rise in rent pushed that restaurant and many others in the area to close or sell to another ambitious restaurateur."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Neyrey cites the example of a local mom and pop Irish pub named Tara Hill, which was located on the corner of Broadway and 108th Street. The rent for Tara Hill went from $15,000 per month during its lease to $35,000 per month from one day to the next."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“When they go to renew their lease and the landlord wants to double the rent, and they’re barely making it on what they’ve had now, that rent, you have to go,” Neyrey said. “So it’s not [that] you go out of business, your lease expires and you close, and that happens to a lot of mom and pop shops. I think that that’s detrimental to the neighborhood. It’s positive in some areas, you get some change and some new restaurants, but to knock out your restaurant kills the charm of the neighborhood or the community, especially when a chain goes in.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Arts & Entertainment editor Noah Sheidlower can be contacted at </i><i>noah.sheidlower@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow him on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/NSheidlower\"><i>@NSheidlower</i></a><i>.</i>"
