            },
            {
              "type": "footer",
              "value": "<p><b>Methodology</b>: Using Google Street View, we “walked” down the streets in the Columbia area and noted what restaurant occupied each space from 2008 through 2019. For most data points, Street View versions were available for 2008, 2009, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2016, 2017, and 2019. We then determined whether these restaurants were single storefronts, New York City based chains, or national chains.</p>"
            }
          ],
          "page_1": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Historically, the Morningside Heights, Hamilton Heights, and West Harlem neighborhoods have been predominantly populated by Black and Latinx communities. In 2000, Morningside Heights and Hamilton Heights in Manhattan Community District 9 were only 20.3 percent white,  29.1 percent Black, and 42.7 percent Hispanic. West Harlem was once a hub for Southern and soul food restaurants, catering to its predominantly working-class population."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Over the past two decades, however, these areas have become home to wealthier and whiter populations. In 2019, Morningside Heights and Hamilton Heights were 35.7 percent white and only 15.2 percent Black and 37 percent Hispanic. During this time period, rent has increased significantly in both areas, leading many people of color to leave the area for neighborhoods like Central and East Harlem or further uptown. Many lower-income populations nearby live in public housing projects, such as the Grant Houses and Frederick Douglass Houses, around which pricier supermarkets and restaurants are opening."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Morningside Heights and West Harlem have attracted a wide range of cuisines that have taken the place of many mom-and-pop restaurants. Along with this, activists have been fighting for access to more affordable and healthier options for lower-income communities, as places around campus have become increasingly trendier and more expensive. Lower-income residents often must travel outside their neighborhoods to cheaper, non-chain grocery stores  or dine at unhealthy local fast-food chains. Additionally, the threat of a West Harlem food hall in Jerome L. Greene Science Center could put more strain on local restaurant owners, offering pricier options."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Gentrification generally begins when investors try to transform affordable communities for their own profit. When newer, more expensive development attracts wealthier and younger people, it leads to major demographic shifts that prices out those originally living in the community. In New York City, the displaced are often people of color who have historically faced issues of racist housing practices."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While gentrification is often analyzed in the context of housing, data reveals that gentrification and restaurants are interconnected. When lower-income minority residents are pushed out of communities, the restaurants catering to these populations often shut down, and when wealthier people move into these communities, they bring with them upscale and trendy eateries, along with higher-end chain restaurants."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Joshua Sbicca, an associate professor of sociology at Colorado State University, restaurants often reflect the processes of gentrification and, in some cases, drive changes in neighborhood class and ethnoracial demographics. Sbicca found that food gentrification can be analyzed both economically and culturally. For instance, lower-income communities may struggle to afford to live in certain areas in cities like New York when developers launch urban agriculture projects to attract new and wealthier residents, even when these projects aim to fill the very gaps they may create."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“As a neighborhood is changing, one of the first things that we would see is a Starbucks or a chain restaurant or chain store that replaces a mom-and-pop local retailer that's been there for generations,” Analena Hassberg, an assistant professor of ethnic and women’s studies at California State Polytechnic University, said. “Food is symbolic of gentrification in a lot of ways because the restaurants, the ones that are coming in, the ones that are getting pushed out, often bring with them this kind of cultural signification of who's in the neighborhood, what kind of income people are bringing in based on the prices at a restaurant.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "When food itself is gentrified, foods culturally important to marginalized groups become \"cool\" and thus, unaffordable. As a result, food retail becomes more upscale, displacing the original restaurants. With this comes what Nevin Cohen, associate professor at the City University of New York Graduate School of Public Health, calls “food mirages,” when high-quality food is priced just out of reach of longtime residents."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Historically, at least, you've seen … the ‘tragic pioneers’ of gentrification: the artists and people who are seeking affordable places to live in the city and who actually kind of appreciate cultural diversity,” Eric Sarmiento, assistant professor in the department of geography at Texas State University, said. “There's also the kind of fetishization of urban authenticity or grittiness, or whatever you want to call it amongst those groups usually.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "To an extent, this phenomenon has occurred recently in Morningside Heights and West Harlem. Restaurants like Taqueria y Fonda, which serves traditional Mexican fare, and Freda’s Caribbean & Soul Cuisine have become favorite spots of many in the community, including Columbia students. The area has seen an uptick in Chinese, Vietnamese, and Indian offerings around campus as well, signifying that even with the emergence of chains, ethnic eateries have remained relatively stable and have grown significantly. While many of these eateries have become trendy—leading many to raise prices over the past decade—others in West Harlem have disappeared, with few remnants of Southern and Latinx cuisines remaining around the new Manhattanville campus."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In Harlem, food gentrification has attracted more European and classic American offerings to historic blocks, which has driven up real estate values and has forced long-time restaurants not only to raise prices, but change menus to cater to a less local audience. While historic cuisines like soul food have struggled to survive in the area, food gentrification in Harlem has also had some positive effects, such as the introduction of healthier options into the community—new restaurants like Seasoned Vegan and healthier supermarkets can help fight obesity in Central Harlem, which has a 31 percent adult obesity rate compared with the city’s overall rate of 24 percent."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Zachary Hyde, an assistant professor at the department of human geography at the University of Toronto, there was a prominent classic model of gentrification in the 1990s that predicted the emergence of chains later in the gentrification process."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Alison Alkon, a professor of sociology at the University of the Pacific and co-editor of the book “A Recipe for Gentrification: Food, Power, and Resistance in the City,” noted that food gentrification occurs in waves. In the first wave of gentrification, “people with maybe a lot of social capital but not a ton of money come in and displace historically marginalized communities in historically redlined neighborhoods,” according to Alkon. This first wave of gentrification greatly impacted West and Central Harlem beginning in the 1980s."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "A <a href=\"https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/pandp.20181034\">Harvard research study</a> found a strong positive correlation between the number of cafés in an area and the number of college-educated residents. The number of cafés increases as neighborhoods become whiter and wealthier. A <a href=\"https://www.eater.com/21194965/gentrification-signs-restaurants-cafes-bars-nyc-chicago-san-francisco-portland\">recent Eater analysis</a> found a high correlation between the number of cafés and rising housing, rent, and income levels in areas of Brooklyn like Crown Heights and Bushwick."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The openings of coffee shops in the last few years like Blue Bottle Coffee, Kuro Kuma Espresso & Coffee, Plowshares Coffee Roasters, and Demitasse Coffee & Tea suggest that this phenomenon might also be occurring around Columbia."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Typically, high-end restaurants do not move into an area early in the gentrification process because the desired clientele does not align with the neighborhood’s makeup, according to Kaaryn Nailor Simmons, director of the Columbia-Harlem Small Business Development Center. This partially explains why a decade ago, newer restaurants along Broadway and Amsterdam Avenue in West Harlem were more inexpensive neighborhood spots, whereas on Broadway near Columbia’s campus, restaurants were more upscale and out of reach for some demographics."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Between 2009-2014, national chains set up shop in seven new locations. Between 2015-2020, this figure rose up to 16, more than double in the same timespan of six years."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Mary Rocco, a term assistant professor in Barnard’s urban studies department, while the traditional model of gentrification envisions a Starbucks, for instance, as the symbol of first-wave gentrification, this is rarely the case in New York anymore. Nowadays, gentrification involves the arrival of niche coffee shops, which then lead to the more upscale eateries."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Rocco claimed that the next wave is fueled by commercial economic interest, which leads to physical “upgrading.” Eventually, that has a displacing effect on small businesses that exist prior to that new wave of gentrification."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "She cited the example of later-stage gentrification in which the Abyssinian Development Corporation pushed for the creation of a new Pathmark in Harlem. While many in the community believed the supermarket would provide healthier options, it also displaced a number of smaller businesses within the footprint and threw a wrench into the affordability of food in East Harlem."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It was also heralded by the community; the community was inherently involved in bringing it to 125th Street as a sort of grocery store that would have a multitude of food options,” Rocco said. “Over time, the Pathmark evolved to what is now sort of the Whole Foods. And so you can see how tastes change in the neighborhood and that’s sort of the acceleration, I think, a little bit of gentrification.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This evolution has been fittingly named the “Whole Foods Effect,” in which specialty grocers with services like a butcher, bakery, and florist can generate price premiums of almost 20 percent. A study by Zillow also found that homes near either Whole Foods or Trader Joe’s cost more and appreciate twice as much as the average U.S. home."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In what is traditionally considered the second wave of gentrification, restaurants become more expensive and physically larger as more young professionals and entrepreneurs move into the area. These entrepreneurs often include restaurant owners who look to cater to a new demographic of residents with higher incomes. Beyond coffee shops, restaurants with waiter service and larger spaces grow during the second wave, sometimes with higher prices than competitors in the neighborhood. According to the Eater analysis, an increase in home prices and waitstaff restaurants are highly correlated in Harlem—the number of wait service restaurants in Harlem grew by over 20 percent as average housing prices soared from $588,000 to $777,000 from 2013 to 2015."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Hassberg, gentrification is “both a physical and cultural phenomenon,” meaning that as more trendy eateries come into a neighborhood, some longer-term residents may feel that the neighborhood is losing its culture. For instance, in an area like West Harlem that has historically been lower-income, many trendier restaurants that have moved in are symbolic of a more affluent perspective. The opposite is also true: Some restaurants might come into an area and appropriate local culture, often to attract tourists."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“So there are the restaurants that are coming in, and it might be something like a brewery or an artisan sandwich place or a new cafe with $15 lattes, and it’s changing the kind of cultural scope and feel of the neighborhood,” Hassberg said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Alkon noted how food gentrification contributes to both material and symbolic exclusion. As high-end restaurants and upscale chains move into an area, some lower-income demographics cannot afford many restaurants in the area. Thus, they are materially excluded from the area. When restaurants change over but the long-term community sticks around, residents can begin to feel that the neighborhood may not be for them anymore."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[Gentrification] leads to feelings of marginalization beyond just the economic exclusion with a feeling that this was our place,” Alkon said. “We built this place. Often, we built this place up under really kind of hard conditions where the kinds of investments that were available to wealthier and whiter communities were systematically denied to low-income, especially Black communities.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "When Marcus Samuelsson opened Red Rooster in Harlem, many in the community considered this as accelerating gentrification, since its prices soared above those of nearby restaurants. Additionally, the restaurant attracted diners from outside the area, many of whom would travel to Harlem only to dine and not explore the area or shop at local stores. Whereas wealthier Black populations in Harlem can afford to dine at these new restaurants, lower-income Black communities may be priced out."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Part of the reason why the cuisines of Harlem and Morningside Heights have remained relatively stable is because of the value placed by affluent communities on perceived authenticity, which oftentimes is associated with lower-priced cuisines. According to Sharon Zukin, professor emerita of sociology at Brooklyn College and the City University of New York Graduate Center, authenticity is a significant vector of what people consider good food."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The people who are really authentic don’t think about being authentic. It’s only the outsiders who look at them, or in this case, it’s outsiders who go to a restaurant that is not really theirs,” Zukin said. “They make a judgment that it’s authentic, but the people who are cooking that food, ‘authentic’ is not really in their vocabulary. It’s not what they’re thinking. They’re thinking, ‘Is it good food? Is it not good food? Is it like the food my mother used to cook or my grandmother used to cook?’ But they’re not thinking in terms of a concept of authenticity.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This phenomenon has been rather pronounced in areas like Harlem, in which many lower-income residents who operated local restaurants and shops had to move out to more affordable areas. Furthermore, while more upscale restaurants like Red Rooster and Sylvia’s attract tourists to the area to sample their world famous food, more local and traditional joints are hit harder by neighborhood outsiders unfamiliar with the cuisine."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Zukin conducted a study with her students comparing Yelp reviews in Bedford-Stuyvesant, a predominantly working-class Black neighborhood, with Greenpoint, a wealthier and whiter neighborhood. As with many Yelp reviews, Zukin hypothesized that many of the reviewers did not patronize the restaurants on a regular basis. She found that when looking at many soul food and Caribbean restaurants in Bed-Stuy which were “not necessarily expensive but were more refined in certain ways and presented themselves differently from most of the local restaurants,” reviews were on the whole more negative than those serving more refined food. Negative reviews often cited factors like greasiness or ambiance as major issues."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In contrast, glowing reviews for Polish restaurants in Greenpoint lauded both food quality and authenticity. Zukin, though, noted that Polish food is quite similar to the Caribbean-style cooking lambasted on Yelp, as both cuisines feature just a few simple core ingredients. According to the paper, the reviews seem to suggest some harm in craving authentic culinary experiences, especially when the number of stars in Yelp reviews is correlated to the volume of business that a restaurant does."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "That people are even eating Caribbean and Polish cuisines is symptomatic of the “democratization of foodie culture” according to Hyde. This process has rendered the act of accruing cultural capital more important than the ability to afford fancy food. Over the last few decades, for instance, people have increasingly eaten across the culinary hierarchy by dining at Michelin star restaurants one day and a hole-in-the-wall food stall the next."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Democratizing food in a low-income neighborhood allows foodies to see themselves as participating in a more democratic process,” Hyde said. “But at the same time, most of the low-income neighborhoods still couldn't afford to eat in restaurants, because they're not Michelin star restaurants, but they're still like $25-30 per plate of food.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "When gentrification reaches its later stages, Hyde noted that there are two main types of displacement that especially impact lower-income communities: forced moves and responsive moves."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Hyde stated that forced moves involve some sort of eviction or the tearing down of a building. Columbia, with the help of the New York state government, has forcibly moved a number of businesses in preparation for the construction of the Manhattanville campus, even going so far as to threaten the use of eminent domain to seize their property. A number of restaurants, including Floridita, were evicted and forced to relocate to 12th Avenue or different neighborhoods."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Hyde, responsive moves differ from evictions in that they are caused by more implicit factors that drive out lower-income residents, like rising rents. Responsive moves strongly impacted restaurants surrounding Manhattanville, as dramatic increases in rent forced owners to decide whether to remain in the area or relocate."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to a paper by Rachel Meltzer, an associate professor of urban policy and chair of the MS public and urban policy program at the Milano School of Policy, displacement is no more prevalent in the typical gentrifying neighborhood than in non-gentrifying neighborhoods. But when businesses do leave gentrified neighborhoods, their old spaces often sit vacant for longer periods of time than in non-gentrified neighborhoods. Ultimately, gentrified neighborhoods usually attract chains to replace displaced businesses."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Smaller businesses cannot afford to stay open once the chains move in, and even some trendier businesses struggle to compete with the influx of huge chains. Finding staff to work at the long-standing restaurants in these neighborhoods also becomes difficult, since employees often cannot afford to live in the neighborhoods of the restaurant.  At restaurants like Ollie’s Noodle Shop & Grille and The Tang Chinese Noodle Bar, for example, many staffers commute from areas with cheaper rents such as Flushing or Chinatown. In areas like the Lower East Side, which has been experiencing gentrification for decades, the number of restaurants is declining yearly."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It seems to me that there's two kinds of restaurants that kind of can make it in this hyper-inflated real estate moment,” Alkon said. “One are the chains, because they have money from the chain, and the other are these venture capital-backed chef-driven projects, so in Harlem, something like Red Rooster.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Some scholars have even pointed to a stage called “super-gentrification,” an intensified period of regentrification in which super-rich financiers displace the original gentrifiers. Although those interviewed disagree on what exact stage of gentrification Morningside Heights and West Harlem are currently in, some have suggested that the area surrounding Columbia is in a state of super-gentrification due to the influx of chains, construction of condos and new high-rises in surrounding neighborhoods, and policing practices around the University."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Another form of late-stage gentrification that has occurred in the areas surrounding Morningside Heights is new-build gentrification, which occurs when new developments move in and chain restaurants purchase large retail storefront on the bottom floors. Oftentimes, developers will make a deal with a particular chain for a 10-year lease even before construction on the building begins."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The phenomenon of late-stage food gentrification becomes more apparent when smaller chains get replaced by larger chains. Aaron Passell, associate director of urban studies at Barnard, pointed to the example of the Shake Shack on Broadway and 116th Street, which replaced the small New York-based Chinese chain restaurant Ollie’s after a fire. Passell noted that in an area like Morningside Heights, this path from smaller business to national chain is rather common."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While Passell acknowledged that the commercial gentrification that goes with a large student population—providing the sorts of consumption opportunities that appeal to students—is real, he also acknowledged that residential gentrification by students is an outstanding question in gentrification scholarship. While the student population stays relatively consistent, the individuals change every year, which is different from when artists and musicians moved into the Lower East Side for longer periods of time. Since there are such varying degrees of disposable income among students who rent in the area and students are short-term renters, their contribution to residential gentrification remains under-researched."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Nonetheless, when people begin to feel excluded from their own neighborhood, especially one that they helped to develop, communities begin to lose their individuality. Alkon described the rise of chains in many neighborhoods as a process of “McDonaldization,” a term coined by sociologist George Ritzer to describe how society takes on the characteristics of a fast-food restaurant. When applied to food gentrification, Alkon noted that as chains become more widespread, places across the country begin to look very similar, destroying the “grooves and intricacies that made things unique in particular places.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think that frustration with the kind of sameness of the suburbs was something that really drove a lot of young folks in my generation to go and try and live in cities and find kind of funky and interesting neighborhoods and create local businesses, and there was kind of a push, a kind of counter-corporate globalization,” Alkon said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Alkon noted how even though there are regular attempts to try to prevent chains moving into cities like New York, it becomes an endless cycle where the chains always seem to win. When people moved back into cities due to the sameness of the suburbs, they were often moving back into neighborhoods where white middle-class people had not formerly lived, such as West Harlem or along Columbus Avenue. At first, this movement led to a rise in experimental and artsy businesses as part of the first-wave of gentrification. Cities like New York are now in later stages of gentrification where prices are so high that the only restaurants that can come back in are chains. As people try to escape chains and the monotony of suburban restaurants, they make their way into urban spaces—essentially following the gentrifiers."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Arts & Entertainment editor Noah Sheidlower can be contacted at </i><i>noah.sheidlower@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow him on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/NSheidlower\"><i>@NSheidlower</i></a><i>.</i>"
            },
            {
