          ],
          "page_2": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The emergence of chains around Columbia, paired with the recent openings of “food gentrifiers,” has led some residents like Dan McSweeney, who works at the Morningside Heights Historic District Committee, to take action. The Morningside Heights that he knew as a center for mom-and-pop eateries has been slowly erased. Along Broadway by campus, national chains and empty storefronts seem to be the new norm; as prices rise, more and more people find themselves feeling like outsiders in their own neighborhoods."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, not all hope is lost. According to McSweeney, 12 local businesses have already signed up to participate in a new initiative tentatively called Morningside Merchants, a small business association for the neighborhood. The association aims to help local businesses in the community stay afloat. This idea came after the Morningside Heights Community Coalition was approached by the New York City Department of Small Business Services, which offered to help educate local restaurants about navigating the resources available to them."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[The community should] promote individual businesses as unique purveyors of goods and services, where they’re establishments that are grounded in the neighborhood. They know the neighborhood. They have elections in the neighborhood, and it’s in the interest of everyone to support that,” McSweeney said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "McSweeney also noted that through this initiative, Columbia students can not only develop relationships with business managers and employees, but also protect the culture of Morningside Heights and West Harlem, which he believes is being taken over by “faceless corporate entities that don’t have any connection to our neighborhood.” Along with this, he claimed that the residents would have an opportunity to promote Morningside Heights as a place of commerce and authentic relationships and “a vibrant shopping and dining district” via outreach campaigns."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think it takes connecting to the stakeholders, establishing a baseline understanding of what is happening right now, and then working toward developing a vision for how the neighborhood develops in terms of its local businesses and overall commerce,” McSweeney said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Analena Hassberg, an assistant professor of ethnic and women’s studies at California State Polytechnic University, believes combatting food gentrification will need to involve policy changes such that people can afford to live in their neighborhood without getting priced out. Hassberg cited common policies like rent control, affordable housing, land trusts, inclusionary zoning policies, and living wage ordinances as essential for resisting the later stages of gentrification."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Because residents are unwittingly or unintentionally complicit in neighborhood gentrification even by just paying rent or dining at more upscale restaurants, according to Hassberg, they should support organizations that are engaged in resisting these changes. Organizations nationwide have been resisting displacement through methods like building gardens, creating co-ops, and implementing a neighborhood barter system to supplement food costs."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“If we want our neighborhoods to look like places with real cultural history and folks who are creating and sustaining a long lineage history in a neighborhood, then we have to support those kinds of [local] establishments, so it’s the choice between Starbucks for your morning coffee or the local cafe, and really being intentional on a personal level,” Hassberg said. “More importantly is thinking about how we put our efforts toward supporting larger structural change, supporting ordinances that are going to create affordable cities for the folks who are at or below the poverty line.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While efforts to clean up neighborhoods and open up healthier groceries can have positive impacts on communities, another contributor to food gentrification around Columbiais the process of green gentrification, a process in which providing “green” amenities drives up rent and attracts wealthier residents to a neighborhood. While the Morningside Heights area has always had numerous parks and green spaces, the introduction of community gardens, green roofs, and energy efficient building materials has likely played a role in making the area more attractive for wealthier residents."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Additionally, the proliferation of green amenities is apparent with the openings of healthier and more expensive supermarkets known as “supermarket greenlining,” which occur when grocers target areas undergoing gentrification and act as ethical businesses concerned about these communities."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[A] strategy that people have used in communities of color and lower-income neighborhoods who have been fighting for environmental justice for decades, now they’re seeing their successes and environmental justice fight are actually helping to grease the wheels for gentrification, which is a really thorny paradox,” Eric Sarmiento, assistant professor in the department of geography at Texas State University, said. “If you manage to get a toxic environment cleaned up, then it actually makes the area more interesting to investors in terms of the gentrification process.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Like Hassberg, Sarmiento emphasized the significance of policy change, specifically social justice initiatives, in slowing food gentrification. He cited the “just green enough” strategy, which strives for environmental justice while trying to maintain well-paid and union jobs in the neighborhood so that green initiatives do not backfire on the communities they are meant to serve."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sarmiento noted that gentrification should not be considered a natural, unstoppable process. For example, very few people in Austin appreciate how rapidly the city is changing and how expensive it is becoming, which has pushed people to think creatively about resisting gentrification."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "One of the solutions Sarmiento cited is the rise of tenant unions—coalitions of both longtime residents and newcomers who organize against landlords who harass or try to evict tenants. In Crown Heights, Brooklyn, 40 buildings have come together to speak in support of a five-year rent freeze, fair renovations, and fair leases, among other demands. Tenant unions have been instrumental in protecting smaller eateries from predatory landlords and assisting restaurants in renegotiating fair leases."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In addition, community benefits agreements have been on the rise throughout the city, which are signed between community groups and real estate developers and require developers to provide communities with certain amenities and benefits. Often, these agreements work to protect small businesses and prevent larger retailers from moving in. The community benefits agreement model was created as a way for communities to participate in planning economic development projects, such as the creation of a new block of restaurants, while ensuring that these projects benefit existing communities."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Aaron Passell, associate director of urban studies at Barnard, who recently published a book on landmark designation in Brooklyn and Baltimore, commented that in addition to rent stabilization laws, designating a neighborhood as a landmark district prevents any significant changes to buildings without those changes being agreed upon by neighborhood preservation activists and approved by city council members. Because of this, small businesses receive additional protections and have additional resources for building maintenance."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Morningside Heights Historic District, approved by the Landmarks Preservation Commission in 2017, consists of 115 residential and institutional buildings, about two-thirds of which date back to between 1900 and 1910. Due to Morningside Heights’ status as a historic district, the effects of gentrification cannot occur to a great extent. Additionally, historic districts receive economic benefits through initiatives like the Historic Preservation Grant Program, which grants tens of thousands of dollars to repair parts of historic buildings, which is particularly beneficial for restaurants that occupy these spaces."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Beyond maintaining the historic buildings in the area, according to Passell, preservation activism also functions as a community-building activity. For example, Crown Heights North Association, which formed as a home for the landmark designation process, also became a place that directed local residents’ attention to struggling mom-and-pop eateries on commercial strips and encouraged support for local retail. What began as a preservation advocacy effort turned into a community building organization that produced significant benefits to long-time residents, such as helping them identify predatory lending practices."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Proposing a landmark district and getting into law requires a significant amount of community organization, [so] it’s frequently the case that the process of designation enables communities to come together in ways that they haven’t previously,” Passell said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "One of the most profound things that Passell noted in his research was that these community organizations helped people become integrated into the neighborhood and learn about its culture and history. If people from different backgrounds can feel strong connections to their community, this indirectly leads them to shop locally and support diversity, fighting against the movement of large corporations into the neighborhood."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“One of the benefits of the Crown Heights North Association was that people began to talk about this neighborhood as a coherent, enduring, positive Black neighborhood with a particular character,” Passell said. “In the oral histories … they’re just beginning to talk about things like that as new people moved into the neighborhood, they didn’t have the habits associated with public space that the longtime residents had. They didn’t know you were supposed to say ‘Hi’ to people when you passed on the sidewalk. And one of the things about building a formal association tasked with the preservation of the neighborhood was it also allowed people to articulate the things that had gone unarticulated about the neighborhood.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "<b> </b><b>COVID-19 and Food Gentrification</b>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although about 90 percent of restaurants in Morningside Heights and West Harlem have reopened or stayed open throughout the pandemic, many had to lay off significant portions of their staff. Restaurants in New York City can now operate at full capacity indoors, but for over a year, many restaurants in the area were operating on takeout and delivery-only models, with others having only some outdoor seating."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Many chain restauransts around campus stayed open throughout the whole pandemic in part because they relied little on indoor dining. While this has kept employment numbers in the area up, many restaurant activists believe the wages paid to workers both before and during the pandemic are too little to live off of—New York City does have a minimum wage of $15 per hour, about double the federal minimum wage. The pandemic has forced many businesses to prioritize keeping their doors open over fighting for fairer wages. When restaurants, specifically mom-and-pop eateries, lack the cash flows to pay living wages, they risk losing members of their staff or closing permanently."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/arts-and-entertainment/2020/04/03/chinese-restaurants-and-independent-eateries-face-heightened-closures-amid-covid-19/\">disparity between chains and single storefronts</a> in Morningside Heights was particularly apparent around the start of the pandemic when 37 out of 66 mom-and-pop shops closed compared with 19 out of 42. Larger chains not only have more economic resources than smaller restaurants, but also have received gigantic Paycheck Protection Program loans and other financial assistance. Chains like Shake Shack even returned their PPP loans since they were intended for smaller businesses. Additionally, the relief bill announcing that restaurants and other businesses employing under 500 people had to give paid sick leave for workers jeopardized the jobs and livelihoods of workers by putting greater strain on small businesses."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Anthony Advincula, director of communications at Restaurant Opportunities Centers United, it is crucial to provide living wages to workers because they would then be able to afford healthier products such as local restaurants in the neighborhood. By providing a living wage, corporate-owned restaurants could find a talented workforce and remain in the community, and small businesses would have larger customer bases since people have more buying power. Paying living wages has a domino effect in that both chains and small businesses can survive."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s really no labor shortage. It is true, around 10 percent of workers in general and restaurant workers, [some] will get more income from the unemployment checks as opposed to working, but that’s a very small fraction of the industry,” Advincula said. “If you calculate their wages—the unemployment checks are based on the calculated wages—the fact that they have low wages to begin with, [and] when you calculate that over a certain period of time, it’s very tiny.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The problem for Advincula, though, is that the issue of fair wages is mainly told from the perspective of the restaurant owner, not the workers. Few restaurant owners would outwardly say that they are not giving substantial living wages to their workers; many assume that employees would work for tips and thus feel little urge to pay higher wages. This power dynamic makes it more difficult for workers to not only fight for better wages but also return to work."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although the pandemic has made it more difficult for restaurant owners to pay higher wages, Mary Rocco, a term assistant professor in Barnard’s urban studies department, noted that in this post-pandemic comeback period, there has been increased support for small food businesses. The NYC Department of Small Business Services has launched a number of campaigns to help owners navigate local grants and encourage residents to buy from local businesses. Initiatives like the Restaurant Revitalization Fund and Fair Share NYC have provided technical assistance to many of the city’s restaurants, which a number of local restaurants have accessed. These programs have been particularly helpful for smaller restaurants that received little funding from federal grants or missed out on other aid opportunities."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The pandemic has created a great divide between chains and non-chains, but in 2020, every borough experienced notable declines in chain stores. In Manhattan, which was hit the hardest, 17.4 percent of chains closed, accounting for about half of all chain store closures. This is the largest annual decline in chain stores since the Center for an Urban Future began collecting data in 2007. Dig, for example, closed 19 of its locations in 2020, while Starbucks closed 49 and Pret a Manger closed 16. The fact that all these chains still have open locations around Columbia suggests the profitability of operating in Morningside Heights."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Alex Turboff, vice president of real estate at BCD, a real estate brokerage firm for restaurants and retail, suggested that the end of the eviction moratorium, which is extended through August 31 for COVID-19-related evictions, and issues surrounding the presence of Good Guy Guarantees may pose challenges for these businesses that have supposedly survived the worst. Good Guy Guarantees are legal promises stating that tenants unable to pay rent for the remaining lease term must give their landlord about three months notice that they will vacate the place, and in return the tenant has to pay fees up until the departure date."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although many chains have closed, some might capitalize on cheaper rents and an increase in empty storefronts along Broadway. However, Andre Neyrey, the owner and president of Blackwood Hospitality, noted that now is an optimal time for new restaurants of all sorts to open due to “pent up demand,” in which people are much more comfortable going out to eat. Around Columbia, many restaurants like Miss Saigon and Bánh have opened on Amsterdam Avenue, and others like Roberta’s are expected to open over the summer."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Additionally, owners might be able to get a fully furnished restaurant for 25 percent rent and no key money or fees paid to landlords to secure leases, while avoiding some costs from plumbing, electrical, ventilation, and others."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s a lot of restaurants, unfortunately, that aren’t going to make it. Most of the rent moratoriums are lifted, and some of these landlords are already stacked up waiting to evict people unfortunately,” Neyrey said. “There’s going to be a lot of space available. Also, rents are much more reduced, because there’s so much inventory now, and as the inventory goes up, the price of them goes down, so you’re going to have better and better rent for a while.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While the future of the restaurant industry remains uncertain, and as more local and national chains move into the area, activists have been fighting to maintain the culture, history, and complexity of the neighborhood, one cup of coffee at a time."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“At the end of the day, this, like every community, is an interdependent collective of people that are influencing each other and supporting each other and so, business has a role in that overall dynamic,” McSweeney said."
            },
            {
